# Git workflow

## Never commit on `main`

- **`main` is protected** — do not commit, push, or implement directly on it.
- Before any code or doc changes, create and switch to a topic branch from up-to-date `main`.
- Merge only via PR; commits land on `main` after review/merge, not from local direct work.

## When to create a branch

Create a topic branch **before** the first commit when:

- Using **superpowers** (brainstorming, writing-plans, executing-plans, subagent-driven development, etc.)
- The task spans **multiple files**, **multiple commits**, or is a **feature/fix/refactor**
- The user asks for a PR or release-related work

Small one-off fixes still get a branch (`fix/…`), not `main`.

## Branch naming

Use lowercase kebab-case: `<type>/<short-topic>`

| Prefix | Use for |
|--------|---------|
| `feat/` | New behavior, user-facing capability |
| `fix/` | Bug fixes |
| `refactor/` | Internal restructuring, no behavior change |
| `docs/` | Documentation-only |
| `chore/` | Tooling, cleanup, deps |
| `ci/` | GitHub Actions, release plumbing |
| `test/` | Test-only changes |

**Examples**

```text
feat/param-omit-defaults
fix/update-sync-deps-venv
docs/git-tag-distribution-spec
chore/cursor-conventional-commits-rule
```

Keep names short (2–4 words), descriptive, and aligned with the PR title.

## Workflow checklist

1. `git fetch origin main && git checkout -b feat/my-topic origin/main`
2. Implement and commit on the branch (see `conventional-commits.mdc` for messages)
3. Push branch and open PR → `main`
4. After merge, delete the remote branch if cleanup is part of the task

## Avoid

```text
git checkout main && git commit          # forbidden
feat/my-topic-with-very-long-name-…      # too vague or too long
my-feature                               # missing type prefix
```
